---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout
  title="About"
  description="701am was built by an operator who spent a decade making education brands findable — back when 'findable' meant Google, and now that it means AI."
>
  <header class="about-hero">
    <div class="hero-atmos"><div class="grid"></div><div class="glow g1"></div><div class="glow g2"></div><div class="glow g3"></div></div>
    <div class="wrap" style="position:relative;z-index:1">
      <div class="eyebrow">About 701am</div>
      <h1>A decade of getting schools <em class="grad">found</em>. Now for the AI era.</h1>
      <p class="lede">701am didn't start as a startup. It started as a problem I'd already spent ten years solving — and watched change overnight.</p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <article class="about-prose">
    <div class="seg">The short version</div>
    <p class="big">I've spent most of my career on one question: when someone is choosing a school, how do they decide — and how do you make sure your program is in that decision?</p>
    <p>For a decade, the answer was search. I built and ran a network of education properties that millions of prospective students used to compare programs — sites like <strong>GradSchoolCenter</strong>, <strong>CollegeCliffs</strong>, <strong>CollegeRanker</strong>, <strong>CollegeChoice</strong>, and <strong>TheBestSchools</strong>. The whole business was understanding exactly how applicants research, what makes a program credible to them, and how to put the right institutions in front of the right students at the moment they were deciding.</p>
    <p>That's not adjacent experience. That <em>is</em> the job 701am does — I just did it for years before the tools existed to automate it.</p>

    <div class="seg">Then the ground moved</div>
    <p>A couple of years ago, the behavior I'd built a career around started to change. Applicants stopped beginning with a Google search and a comparison site. They started asking an AI assistant — <em>"what's the best online MSW for working adults?"</em> — and taking the short, confident answer it gave them.</p>
    <p class="pull">The shortlist was forming somewhere I couldn't see, in a place I couldn't optimize for with the old playbook.</p>
    <p>I watched institutions that had spent years and fortunes on their visibility quietly disappear from the answer. Not because their programs got worse — because the place the decision happened moved, and nobody had built the machine to follow it there.</p>

    <div class="seg">Why 701am exists</div>
    <p>The signals that make a program credible haven't actually changed. Rankings. Real outcomes data. Coverage in publications people trust. Those still decide who gets shortlisted — it's just that <strong>an AI reads them now too</strong>, alongside the humans. The work that earns those signals is the same work I've done for a decade. It's just slow, manual, and expensive — which is why most institutions only do it in bursts, around a campaign, and then let it reset.</p>
    <p>701am is the machine I wish I'd had: a swarm of agents that does that earned-media work continuously, so a school's visibility compounds instead of resetting — and so it shows up in the AI answer, the search result, and the press, all at once.</p>
    <p class="pull">I'm not a PR person who discovered AI. I'm an education-visibility operator who spent ten years on this exact problem, building the tool the next ten years need.</p>

    <div class="seg">Who I work with</div>
    <p>Everything here points at higher ed, because that's where I have an unfair advantage and no interest in pretending otherwise. I build for the institutions enrolling students, the edtech and online-program companies selling into them, and the agencies that serve them — the three corners of the same world I've worked in for years.</p>
    <p>If you're in one of those corners, you're not explaining your world to me. I already know it.</p>
  </article>

  <!-- CREDENTIALS -->
  <section class="creds">
    <div class="atmos"><div class="dg dg1"></div></div>
    <div class="inner">
      <div class="wrap">
        <div class="ch">
          <div class="eb">The track record</div>
          <h2>Not a first attempt at education visibility.</h2>
          <p>The numbers below are the kind I'd put here — replace with your verified figures before launch.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="creds-grid">
          <div class="cred"><div class="cv">10+</div><div class="cl">Years in education lead generation and visibility</div></div>
          <div class="cred"><div class="cv">5+</div><div class="cl">Education comparison properties built and operated</div></div>
          <div class="cred"><div class="cv">Millions</div><div class="cl">Of prospective students reached across those properties</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="creds-foot">Figures are illustrative placeholders — substantiate before launch.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PAST WORK -->
  <section class="past">
    <div class="ph">
      <div class="eb">Built &amp; operated</div>
      <h2>A network applicants actually used.</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="past-list">
      <span class="pl">GradSchoolCenter</span>
      <span class="pl">CollegeCliffs</span>
      <span class="pl">CollegeRanker</span>
      <span class="pl">CollegeChoice</span>
      <span class="pl">TheBestSchools</span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- VALUES -->
  <section class="values">
    <div class="value">
      <i class="ti ti-shield-check"></i>
      <div><h3>Earned, never faked</h3><p>No fabricated coverage, no invented quotes, no manufactured rankings. Earned media only works if it's actually earned — and in higher ed, anything less is a liability.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="value">
      <i class="ti ti-arrows-up-right"></i>
      <div><h3>Visibility should compound</h3><p>The old model resets every campaign. We build so every placement, ranking, and citation makes the next one easier — visibility as an asset, not a recurring expense.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="value">
      <i class="ti ti-focus-2"></i>
      <div><h3>One world, done deeply</h3><p>We don't serve every industry. We serve higher ed, because depth beats breadth — and because it's the world we actually know.</p></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CLOSING -->
  <section class="closing">
    <div class="catmos"><div class="cg"></div></div>
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="pill-badge"><span class="tagm">Filed at sunrise</span></div>
      <h2>Let's get your program <em class="grad">found</em>.</h2>
      <p>701am is opening to a first group of higher-ed teams. I'd like yours to be one of them.</p>
      <button class="btn btn-primary btn-lg js-soon"><i class="ti ti-sparkles"></i>Request early access</button>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
